<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN CHARITY GROUP `SPREADS LOVE' IN INDIA
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Delhi, India, Feb. 14 (CNA) 02/14/07  17:26:39 (By Paul Kuo
and T.C. Jiang)
</P>
<P>
The Chou Ta-kuan Cultural and Educational Foundation sent a five-
member delegation on a visit to a national cancer research center
in India Tuesday to express care for the center's hospitalized
children.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Foundation Founder Chou Chin-hua, brought
books and gifts to the children at the Rajiv Gandhi Cancer
Institute and Research Center, accompanied by Elliott Chang, a
deputy chief at Taiwan's representative office in India.
</P>
<P>
Praising the center's doctors for accepting low wages to serve
the children, Chou suggested to the center that it recommend
model doctors and children to his foundation, which will invite
them to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The next day, the delegation presented the 9th "Global Love for
Life" award to Gobinda Pradhan, a gangster-turned-founder of a
charity, to recognize his efforts to help prisoners in India.
</P>
<P>
The delegation also gave a book written by Chou Ta-kuan to Sri
Sri Ravi Shankar, founder of the Art of Living Foundation. The
foundation was established in 1981 and is dedicated to the
promotion of purified life and good health.
</P>
<P>
The Chou Ta-kuan Cultural and Educational Foundation, founded in
1997, is named after the founder's son, who died of cancer at the
age of 10. Each year, the foundation gives a "Global Love for
Life" award to a person who demonstrates great passion for life
and bravely faces challenges.
</P>
